05834nam a22008295i 9780812293685DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979744656  a97808122936857 a10.9783/97808122936852doi  a(DE-B1597)481193  a(OCoLC)969646213  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHN659.Z9 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a303.62231 aHermez, Sami, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar Is Coming :bBetween Past and Future Violence in Lebanon /cSami Hermez. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b20 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Translation -- tTimeline of Key Historical Moments -- tMajor Political Parties and Political Blocs -- tList of Characters -- tChapter 1. In the Meanwhile: Theory and Fieldwork in Protracted Conflict -- tChapter 2. War, Politics, and Lunch: Conversations of Everyday Life -- tChapter 3. “At the Gates of War”: Time, Space, and the Anticipation of Political Violence -- tChapter 4. “This Is Our Life”: Experiencing the Intensification of Political Violence -- tChapter 5. Enframing the Anticipation of War -- tChapter 6. Active Forgetting and the Memory of War in Everyday Life -- tChapter 7. Ambiguities of War’s Remembrance: Two Episodes -- tChapter 8. Amnesty as a Politics of Protracted Conflict -- tContinuations. The Anticipation of War in 2009– 2014 -- tAppendix 1. The Cairo Agreement -- tAppendix 2. The Doha Agreement -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom 1975 to 1990, Lebanon experienced a long war involving various national and international actors. The peace agreement that followed and officially propelled the country into a "postwar" era did not address many of the root causes of war, nor did it hold main actors accountable. Instead, a politics of "no victor, no vanquished" was promoted, in which the political elite agreed simply to consign the war to the past. However, since then, Lebanon has found itself still entangled in various forms of political violence, from car bombings and assassinations to additional outbreaks of armed combat.In War Is Coming, Sami Hermez argues that the country's political leaders have enabled the continuation of violence and examines how people live between these periods of conflict. What do everyday conversations, practices, and experiences look like during these moments? How do people attempt to find a measure of certainty or stability in such times? Hermez's ethnographic study of everyday life in Lebanon between the volatile years of 2006 and 2009 tackles these questions and reveals how people engage in practices of recollecting past war while anticipating future turmoil. Hermez demonstrates just how social interactions and political relationships with the state unfold and critically engages our understanding of memory and violence, seeing in people's recollections living and spontaneous memories that refuse to forget the past. With an attention to the details of everyday life, War Is Coming shows how even a conversation over lunch, or among friends, may turn into a discussion about both past and future unrest.Shedding light on the impact of protracted conflict on people's everyday experiences and the way people anticipate political violence, Hermez highlights an urgency for alternative paths to sustaining political and social life in Lebanon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 4aAnthropology. 4aFolklore. 4aHuman Rights. 4aLaw. 4aLinguistics. 4aPolitical Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / A